o-Owner David Blitzer Will Return to Scotch Plains-Fanwood High School for Hall of Fame Induction  |publisher=[[TAPinto]] Springfield|date= December 9, 2018|url=https://www.tapinto.net/towns/springfield/sections/union-county-news/articles/nj-devils-co-owner-david-blitzer-will-return-to-scotch-plains-fanwood-high-school-for-hall-of-fame-induction-27  |accessdate=}}</ref> He graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1991. He is married to fellow Penn alumnus Allison Ross.<ref>[http://www.upenn.edu/gazette/0101/0101notes.html University of Pennsylvania Gazette] retrieved July 7, 2013</ref> In 1991, he accepted a position with the [[Blackstone Group]] where he serves as Senior Managing Director & Head of Tactical Opportunities in [[New York City]].<ref>[http://www.blackstone.com/the-firm/our-people/david-s-blitzer Blackstone Group: Our People - David S. Blitzer] retrieved July 7, 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first= David |last= Smagalla |authorlink=   |title= In Their Own Words With Blackstone Group's David Blitzer  |publisher=[[Wall Street Journal]]|date=December 27, 2017 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-their-own-words-with-blackstone-groups-david-blitzer-1514377800  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nBlitzer is a member of the investment group that won a $280 million bid for the purchase of the Philadelphia 76ers. The other members of the investment group are: [[Joshua Harris (businessman)|Joshua Harris]] of the private equity firm [[Apollo Global Management]], portfolio manager [[Art Wrubel]], and former NBA agent and Sacramento Kings executive [[Jason Levien]], all fellow Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania graduates,<ref name=PhillyCompetitionSuccess>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-08-02/sports/29842441_1_sixers-apollo-global-management-joshua-harris Philadelphia Inquirer: \"Those who know him say Joshua Harris, soon-to-be Sixers owner, lives for competition and success\" By Kate Fagan] August 02, 2011</ref>  as well as former [[Vail Resorts]] CEO [[Adam Aron]], [[Martin J. Geller]], [[David B. Heller]], Travis Hennings, [[James Lassiter]], [[Marc J. Leder|Marc Leder]], [[Michael G. Rubin|Michael Rubin]], [[Will Smith]] & [[Jada Pinkett Smith]], and Indonesian businessmen Handy Soetedjo & [[Erick Thohir]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/sixers/stories/group_led_by_joshua_harris_com_2011_10_18.html ESPN: \"Group led by Joshua Harris completes purchase of Sixers\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018020218/http://www.nba.com/sixers/stories/group_led_by_joshua_harris_com_2011_10_18.html# |date=2013-10-18 }} October 18, 2011</ref> Comcast-Spectacor and Harris began talks in the summer of 2011.  The deal was announced on July 13, 2011.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6767259/sale-philadelphia-76ers-joshua-harris-group Sale of 76ers to Joshua Harris finished]. [[ESPN]], 2011-07-13.</ref>  The NBA formally approved the deal on October 13.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/sixers/stories/group_led_by_joshua_harris_com_2011_10_18.html Group led by Joshua Harris completes purchase of 76ers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131018020218/http://www.nba.com/sixers/stories/group_led_by_joshua_harris_com_2011_10_18.html# |date=2013-10-18 }}. [[Philadelphia 76ers]], 2011-10-13.</ref> As of August 2019, the value of the Sixers has increased to $1.7 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= NBA Team Valuations\" #12 Philadelphia 76ers  |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date= August 2019|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/philadelphia-76ers/#35062f3c764f  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2013, it was announced that a group led by Joshua Harris and partner David Blitzer have purchased a majority stake in the [[New Jersey Devils]] of the [[NHL]], which includes the rights to operate [[Prudential Center]] arena in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. The transaction was reportedly for over $320 million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Devils announce sale of team to billionaire Josh Harris|first=|work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=August 15, 2013|url = http://www.nj.com/devils/index.ssf/2013/08/hold_devils_announce_sale_of_team.html#incart_m-rpt-1}}</ref><ref>[http://jewishexponent.com/newsmakers-week-of-aug-29-2013 Jewish Exponent: \"Josh Harris, owner of the Philadelphia 76ers, has, with David Blitzer, purchased the New Jersey Devils in the NHL for $320 million\" By Michael Elkin] August 28, 2013</ref> In 2017, Blitzer and Harris formed [[Harris Blitzer Sports & Entertainment]] (HBSE) which will hold all their sports investments; Harris will serve as Owner/Chairman and Blitzer as Owner/Vice-Chairman.<ref>{{Cite web|first= Jessica |last=Camerato |authorlink=   |title=Sixers owners Josh Harris, David Blitzer form sports and entertainment business   |publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=September 25, 2017 |url=https://www.nbcsports.com/philadelphia/philadelphia-76ers/sixers-owners-josh-harris-david-blitzer-form-sports-and-entertainment-business  |accessdate=}}</ref> As of August 2019, the value of the Devils has increased to $455 million.<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title= NHL Team Valuations\" #19 New Jersey Devils  |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date= August 2019|url=https://www.forbes.com/teams/new-jersey-devils/#e8b6015b37ea|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, he partnered with David Abrams and lead a local investment group that purchased a 50% interest the [[New York Yankees]] [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] affiliate, the [[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders]];<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title=Mandalay Announces Pending Sale of Ownership Interest in RailRiders   |publisher=[[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders]]|date= September 3, 2014  |url=https://www.milb.com/scranton-wb/news/mandalay-announces-pending-sale-of-ownership-interest-in-railriders/c-92913450  |accessdate=}}</ref> Blitzer and Abrams will serve as co-managing owners.<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title=RailRiders Unveil Members of Local Ownership |publisher=[[Scranton/Wilkes-Barre RailRiders]]|date=February 25, 2015  |url=https://www.milb.com/scranton-wb/news/railriders-unveil-members-of-local-ownership/c-109821612|accessdate=}}</ref> In December 2015, Blizer and Harris joined with [[Steve Parish (businessman)|Steve Parish]] to a take a controlling stake in [[Crystal Palace F.C.]]<ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title=Palace agree \u00a350m US investment from New Jersey Devils owner   |publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date= December 18, 2015|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/dec/18/crystal-palace-us-investment-josh-harris  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Blizer and Harris purchased ''[[Dignitas (esports)|Dignitas]]'', a professional [[esports]] organization based in the [[United Kingdom]] formed when ''[[Battlefield 1942]]'' [[Clan (computer gaming)|clans]] Legion Condor and Sweden Kompanix merged. It best known for its former [[League of Legends]] and [[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]] squads.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rovell|first1=Darren|title=76ers acquire esports teams Dignitas and Apex|url=http://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/17637299/76ers-acquire-esports-teams-dignitas-apex|accessdate=9 October 2016|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=26 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\nBlitzer and his wife founded the Blitzer Family Foundation which promotes youth development through education, athletics, and health.<ref name=TAPReturn /> Blitzer serves on the Boards of Dream, a youth development organizing servicing more than 2,200 inner city children, the [[Riverdale Country School]], the Advisory Board of the [[Mount Sinai Hospital (Manhattan)|Mount Sinai Hospital]] Surgical Department, the Board of Overseers at the [[Wharton School]], and the Board of Trustees at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=TAPReturn /> Blitzer is a supporter of [[Hillel: The Foundation for Jewish Campus Life|Hillel]], which focuses on encouraging Jewish undergraduate and graduate students to embrace their Jewish heritage.<ref>[http://www.hillel.org/docs/default-source/annual-reports/annualreport2012.pdf?sfvrsn=2 Hillel Organization: \"2012 Annual report\"] 2012</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBlitzer is married to Allison (n\u00e9e Ross) Blitzer, who is also Jewish;<ref>[https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-186021913/11m-family-feud-rocks-private-equity-world-at-loggerheads The Evening Standard: \"$11M Family Feud Rocks Private Equity World; at Loggerheads: Stuart Ross, above Left with His Attorney, Stuart Jackson, and His Son-in-Law, David Blitzer, Far Right\"] September 30, 2008</ref> they have five children between the ages of 10-17.\n\nIn 2010, his father-in-law, Stuart Ross, who once owned the North American rights to the [[Smurfs]] franchise, was convicted of trying to extort $5.5 million from Blitzer in return for having no more contact with Blitzer's family and another $5.5 million from Blitzer for having no more contact with Blitzer and Blackstone. He was convicted of extortion and sentenced to five years of probation under the condition that he get psychiatric and alcohol treatment and has no contact with his daughter Allison, Blitzer, their children, and the Blackstone Group.<ref>Rothfield, Michael. [https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903352704576540810122580554 Wall Street Journal: \"New Tack in Extortion Case - Blackstone Executive Now Being Sued by His Father-in-Law's Former Attorney\"], ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', September 3, 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/manhattan/importer_extortion_smurfs_takes_ogzNEti6KSFuXuiX7YW7tJ New York Post: \"Importer of 'Smurfs' takes plea in wacky $11.5 million Blackstone Group extortion case\" By LAURA ITALIANO] August 12, 2010</ref><ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-07/father-in-law-of-blackstone-director-blitzer-faces-july-26-extortion-trial.html Bloomberg: \"Father-in-Law of Blackstone Director Blitzer Faces July 26 Extortion Trial\" By Karen Freifeld] June 7, 2010</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Philadelphia 76ers}}\n{{NBAOwners}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blitzer, David S.}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:The Blackstone Group people]]\n[[Category:New Jersey Devils executives]]\n[[Category:People from Scotch Plains, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia 76ers owners]]\n[[Category:Scotch Plains-Fanwood High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Union County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 10-17 \u2192 10\u201317, replaced: 0 million \u2192 0\u00a0million (8)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_S._Blitzer"}
{"title_page": "Moody River", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Moody River\n| cover      = Moody River by Pat Boone single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = ''Moody River'' by Pat Boone\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Pat Boone]]\n| album      = Moody River\n| B-side     = A Thousand Years\n| released   = May 1961\n| format     = 45 rpm\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country pop]]\n| length     = 2:41\n| label      = [[Dot Records|Dot]]\n| writer     = Gary D. Bruce\n| producer   = [[Randy Wood (record producer)|Randy Wood]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Moody_River_by_Pat_Boone.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Moody River'''\" is a song released in May 1961, which was performed by [[Pat Boone]].  It reached number-one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart the following month.<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>  It was written by and originally performed by country rockabilly singer Chase Webster (real name Gary Daniel Bruce, not to be confused with Gary Bruce of [[the Knack]]). Webster was a labelmate of Boone's at Dot Records.\n\nThis was the title track from one of Boone's better-selling albums. Boone sang this song as if he were in pain.  It was covered some years later by Johnny Burnette in 1962, also [[Frank Sinatra]] and [[Johnny Rivers]]. In August 2009, [[John Fogerty]] covered the song in the album entitled ''[[The Blue Ridge Rangers Rides Again]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe song tells the story of a man who goes to meet his love at the river, by the old oak tree, and finds that she has committed suicide.  A note on the riverbank explains that she has cheated on him and that \"No longer can I live with this hurt and this sin.  I just couldn't tell you that guy was just a friend.\" He then looks into the river and sees his own reflection on the river looking back, ever hauntingly, at him. He is the \"lonely, lonely face just lookin' back at me\". So with \"Tears in his eyes, and a prayer on his lips, and the glove of his lost love, at his fingertips\".\n\n== Chart performance ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1961)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ([[CHUM]] ''Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://chumtribute.com/61-06-26-chart.jpg CHUM Tribute Charts, June 26, 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|New Zealand (''Lever Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qartistid=175#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 20 July 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.K. Singles charts\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. Adult Contemporany\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Hot 100 number-one singles of 1961 (U.S.)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928041734/http://www.bear-family.de/tabel1/product/bcd16776_e.htm Pat Boone at Bear Family Records]\n* {{YouTube|AzpoZyiLLwA|Video of original recording by Chase Webster}}\n* [http://www.beachwoodreporter.com/music/pat_boone_moody_river.php \"Beachwood Reporter\" background and commentary on Moody River]\n\n[[Category:1961 singles]]\n[[Category:Pat Boone songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Songs about suicide]]\n[[Category:Teenage tragedy songs]]\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:Dot Records singles]]\n\n\n{{1960s-single-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Moody River\n| cover      = Moody River by Pat Boone single cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = ''Moody River'' by Pat Boone\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Pat Boone]]\n| album      = Moody River\n| B-side     = A Thousand Years\n| released   = May 1961\n| format     = 45 rpm\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country pop]]\n| length     = 2:41\n| label      = [[Dot Records|Dot]]\n| writer     = Gary D. Bruce\n| producer   = [[Randy Wood (record producer)|Randy Wood]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Audio sample\n | type = single\n | file = Moody_River_by_Pat_Boone.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Moody River'''\" is a song released in May 1961, which was performed by [[Pat Boone]].  It reached number-one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart the following month.<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>  It was written by and originally performed by country rockabilly singer Chase Webster (real name Gary Daniel Bruce, not to be confused with Gary Bruce of [[the Knack]]). Webster was a labelmate of Boone's at Dot Records.\n\nThis was the title track from one of Boone's better-selling albums. Boone sang this song as if he were in pain.  It was covered some years later by Johnny Burnette in 1962, also [[Frank Sinatra]] and [[Johnny Rivers]]. In August 2009, [[John Fogerty]] covered the song in the album entitled ''[[The Blue Ridge Rangers Rides Again]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nThe song tells the story of a man who goes to meet his love at the river, by the old oak tree, and finds that she has committed suicide.  A note on the riverbank explains that she has cheated on him and that \"No longer can I live with this hurt and this sin.  I just couldn't tell you that guy was just a friend.\" He then looks into the river and sees his own reflection on the river looking back, ever hauntingly, at him. He is the \"lonely, lonely face just lookin' back at me\". So with \"Tears in his eyes, and a prayer on his lips, and the glove of his lost love, at his fingertips\".\n\n== Chart performance ==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1961)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Canada ([[CHUM]] ''Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://chumtribute.com/61-06-26-chart.jpg CHUM Tribute Charts, June 26, 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|New Zealand (''Lever Hit Parade'')<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20lever&qartistid=175#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 20 July 1961]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.K. Singles charts\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>''Joel Whitburn's Top Pop Singles 1955\u20131990'' - {{ISBN|0-89820-089-X}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. Adult Contemporany\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Hot 100 number-one singles of 1961 (U.S.)]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070928041734/http://www.bear-family.de/tabel1/product/bcd16776_e.htm Pat Boone at Bear Family Records]\n* {{YouTube|AzpoZyiLLwA|Video of original recording by Chase Webster}}\n* [http://www.beachwoodreporter.com/music/pat_boone_moody_river.php \"Beachwood Reporter\" background and commentary on Moody River]\n\n[[Category:1961 singles]]\n[[Category:Pat Boone songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Canada]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Songs about suicide]]\n[[Category:Teenage tragedy songs]]\n[[Category:1961 songs]]\n[[Category:Dot Records singles]]\n\n\n{{1960s-single-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moody_River"}
{"title_page": "Dyskinesia", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Dyskinetic cerebral palsy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Dyskinesia \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| field           = [[Neurology]] \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Dyskinesia''' refers to a category of [[movement disorder]]s that are characterized by involuntary muscle movements,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dyskinesia (Health Article)|url=http://health.yahoo.net/galecontent/dyskinesia|publisher=Yahoo! Health|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> including movements similar to [[tic]]s or [[Choreia (disease)|chorea]] and diminished voluntary movements.<ref>{{DorlandsDict|three/000033093|dyskinesia}}</ref> Dyskinesia can be anything from a slight tremor of the hands to an uncontrollable movement of the upper body or lower extremities. Discoordination can also occur internally especially with the respiratory muscles and it often goes unrecognized.{{sfn|Healy|2008|p=29-30}} Dyskinesia is a [[symptom]] of several [[medical disorder]]s that are distinguished by their underlying cause.\n\n==Types==\n===Medication-induced dyskinesias===\nAcute [[dystonia]] is a sustained muscle contraction that sometimes appears soon after administration of [[antipsychotic]] medications.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\">{{cite book|editor1=Brian K. Alldredge|display-editors=etal|title=Applied therapeutics : the clinical use of drugs.|date=2013|publisher=Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-1609137137|page=1937|edition=10th}}</ref> Any muscle in the body may be affected, including the jaw, tongue, throat, arms, or legs. When the throat muscles are involved, this type of dystonia is called an acute [[laryngospasm]] and is a medical emergency because it can impair breathing.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\" /> Older antipsychotics such as [[Haloperidol]] or [[Fluphenazine]] are more likely to cause acute dystonia than newer agents. Giving high doses of antipsychotics by injection also increases the risk of developing acute dystonia.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\" />\n\n[[Methamphetamine]], other [[amphetamines]] and [[dopaminergic]] [[stimulants]] including [[cocaine]] and [[pemoline]] can produce [[choreoathetoid]] dyskinesias; the prevalence, time-frame and [[prognosis]] are not well established.  Amphetamines also cause a dramatic increase in choreoathetoid symptoms in patients with underlying [[chorea]] such as [[Sydenham's chorea|Sydenham's]], [[Huntington's disease|Huntington's]], and [[Lupus]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rusinyak|first1=Daniel E.|title=Neurologic manifestations of chronic methamphetamine abuse|journal=Neurologic Clinics|date=2011|volume=29|issue=3|pages=641\u2013655|doi=10.1016/j.ncl.2011.05.004|pmc=3148451|accessdate=|pmid=21803215}}</ref>  Long-term use of amphetamines may increase the risk of [[Parkinson's disease|Parkinson's disease (PD)]]:  in one [[retrospective study]] with over 40,000 participants it was concluded that amphetamine abusers generally had a 200% higher chance of developing PD versus those with no history of abuse; the risk was much higher in women, almost 400%.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hanson|first1=Glen R.|last2=Fleckenstein|first2=Annette E.|last3=Curtin|first3=Kare|title=Dependence on amphetamines increases Parkinson's disease: Effect of gender|journal=Drug and Alcohol Dependence|date=January 1, 2015|volume=146|pages=e134\u2013e135|doi=10.1016/j.drugalcdep.2014.09.284|url=http://www.drugandalcoholdependence.com/article/S0376-8716(14)01346-5/fulltext|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>  There remains some controversy as of 2017.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kish|first1=Stephen J.|last2=Boileau|first2=Isabelle|last3=Callaghan|first3=Russell C.|last4=Tong|first4=Junchao|title=Brain dopamine neurone 'damage': methamphetamine users vs. Parkinson's disease \u2013 a critical assessment of the evidence|journal=European Journal of Neuroscience|date=2017|volume=45|issue=1|pages=58\u201366|doi=10.1111/ejn.13363|pmid=27519465|pmc=5209286}}</ref>\n\n[[Levodopa-induced dyskinesia]] (LID) is evident in patients with Parkinson's disease who have been on [[levodopa]] ({{L-DOPA}}) for prolonged periods of time. LID commonly first appears in the foot, on the most affected side of the body. There are three main types that can be classified on the basis of their course and clinical presentation following an oral dose of {{L-DOPA}}:<ref name=\"Fabbrini\"/><ref name=\"Thanvi\"/>\n\n* '''Off-period dystonia''' \u2013 correlated to the [[akinesia]] that occurs before the full effect of {{L-DOPA}} sets in, when the plasma levels of {{L-DOPA}} are low. In general, it occurs as painful spasms in the foot. Patients respond to {{L-DOPA}} therapy.<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/>\n* '''Diphasic dyskinesia''' \u2013 occurs when [[blood plasma|plasma]] L-DOPA levels are rising or falling. This form occurs primarily in the lower limbs (though they can happen elsewhere) and is usually [[dystonic]] (characterized by apparent rigidity within muscles or groups thereof) or [[wikt:ballistic|ballistic]] (characterized by involuntary movement of muscles) and will not respond to {{L-DOPA}} dosage reductions.<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/>\n* '''Peak-dose dyskinesia''' \u2013 the most common form of levodopa-induced dyskinesia; it correlates with the plateau {{L-DOPA}} plasma level. This type usually involves the upper limbs more (but could also affect the head, trunk and respiratory muscles), is choreic (of chorea), and less disabling. Patients will respond to {{L-DOPA}} reduction but may be accompanied by deterioration of [[parkinsonism]].<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/> Peak-dose L-DOPA-induced dyskinesia has {{As of|2013|07|alt=recently}} been suggested to be associated with cortical dysregulation of dopamine signaling.<ref name=\"Tamte\"/>\n\n===Chronic or tardive===\nLate-onset dyskinesia, also known as [[tardive dyskinesia]], occurs after long-term treatment with an [[antipsychotic]] drug such as [[haloperidol]] (Haldol) or [[amoxapine]] (Asendin). The symptoms include tremors and writhing movements of the body and limbs, and abnormal movements in the face, mouth, and tongue{{spaced ndash}} including involuntary lip smacking, repetitive pouting of the lips, and tongue protrusions.{{sfn|Healy|2008|p=30\u201331}}\n\n[[Rabbit syndrome]] is another type of chronic dyskinesia, while [[orofacial dyskinesia]] may be related to persistent replication of [[Herpes simplex virus type 1]].<ref name=\"Gonazales\" />\n\n===Non-motor===\nTwo other types, [[primary ciliary dyskinesia]] and [[biliary dyskinesia]], are caused by specific kinds of ineffective movement of the body, and are not [[movement disorder]]s.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Akathisia]]\n* [[Akinesia]]\n* [[Dopamine]]\n* [[Hemiballismus]]\n* [[Management of Parkinson's disease#Medication|Medication Management of Parkinson's disease]]\n* [[Paroxysmal dyskinesia]]\n* [[Psychosis]]\n* [[Schizophrenia]]\n* [[Serotonin]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Fabbrini\">\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Fabbrini G, Brotchie JM, Grandas F, Nomoto M, Goetz CG |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesias |journal=Movement Disorders Society |date=April 2007 |volume=22 |issue=10 |pages=1379\u201389 |doi=10.1002/mds.21475 |pmid=17427940}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tamte\">\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Halje P, Tamt\u00e8 M, Richter U, Mohammed M, Cenci MA, Petersson P |date=November 2012 |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesia is strongly associated with resonant cortical oscillations |journal=Journal of Neuroscience |volume=32 |issue=47 |pages=16541\u201351 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3047-12.2012 |pmid=23175810 |pmc=6621755 |url=http://www.jneurosci.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=23175810 |accessdate=30 November 2013}} {{open access}} {{link note|note=full free text}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Thanvi>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Thanvi B, Lo N, Robinson T |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesia in Parkinson's disease: clinical features, pathogenesis, prevention and treatment |journal=Postgraduate Medical Journal |date=June 2007 |volume=83 |issue=980 |pages=384\u201388 |doi=10.1136/pgmj.2006.054759 |pmid=17551069 |pmc=2600052}} {{open access}} {{link note|note=full free text}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gonazales\">\n{{cite journal |title=Postherpes simplex type 1 neuralgia simulating postherpetic neuralgia |journal=J Pain Symptom Manage |date=July 1992 |volume=7 |issue=5 |pages=320\u20133 |pmid=1624816 |author=Gonzales GR |doi=10.1016/0885-3924(92)90065-p}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book |author=David Healy |title=Psychiatric Drugs Explained |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ikTJViYMPIEC |accessdate=16 December 2010 |date=3 December 2008 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=978-0-7020-2997-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 17912\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|G|24|9|g|20}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|333.8}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = \n| eMedicineSubj   = \n| eMedicineTopic  = \n| MeshID          = D020820\n| SNOMED CT       = 9748009\n}}\n{{CNS diseases of the nervous system}}\n{{Nervous and musculoskeletal system symptoms and signs}}\n\n[[Category:Symptoms and signs: Nervous system]]\n[[Category:Parkinson's disease]]\n[[Category:Neurological disorders]]\n[[Category:Extrapyramidal and movement disorders]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Dyskinetic cerebral palsy}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Dyskinesia \n| image           =  \n| caption         =  \n| field           = [[Neurology]] \n| \n| pronounce       =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\n'''Dyskinesia''' refers to a category of [[movement disorder]]s that are characterized by involuntary muscle movements,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dyskinesia (Health Article)|url=http://health.yahoo.net/galecontent/dyskinesia|publisher=Yahoo! Health|accessdate=25 January 2014}}</ref> including movements similar to [[tic]]s or [[Choreia (disease)|chorea]] and diminished voluntary movements.<ref>{{DorlandsDict|three/000033093|dyskinesia}}</ref> Dyskinesia can be anything from a slight tremor of the hands to an uncontrollable movement of the upper body or lower extremities. Discoordination can also occur internally especially with the respiratory muscles and it often goes unrecognized.{{sfn|Healy|2008|p=29-30}} Dyskinesia is a [[symptom]] of several [[medical disorder]]s that are distinguished by their underlying cause.\n\n==Types==\n===Medication-induced dyskinesias===\nAcute [[dystonia]] is a sustained muscle contraction that sometimes appears soon after administration of [[antipsychotic]] medications.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\">{{cite book|editor1=Brian K. Alldredge|display-editors=etal|title=Applied therapeutics : the clinical use of drugs.|date=2013|publisher=Wolters Kluwer Health/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|location=Baltimore|isbn=978-1609137137|page=1937|edition=10th}}</ref> Any muscle in the body may be affected, including the jaw, tongue, throat, arms, or legs. When the throat muscles are involved, this type of dystonia is called an acute [[laryngospasm]] and is a medical emergency because it can impair breathing.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\" /> Older antipsychotics such as [[Haloperidol]] or [[Fluphenazine]] are more likely to cause acute dystonia than newer agents. Giving high doses of antipsychotics by injection also increases the risk of developing acute dystonia.<ref name=\"Applied Therapeutics Acute Dystonia\" />\n\n[[Methamphetamine]], other [[amphetamines]] and [[dopaminergic]] [[stimulants]] including [[cocaine]] and [[pemoline]] can produce [[choreoathetoid]] dyskinesias; the prevalence, time-frame and [[prognosis]] are not well established.  Amphetamines also cause a dramatic increase in choreoathetoid symptoms in patients with underlying [[chorea]] such as [[Sydenham's chorea|Sydenham's]], [[Huntington's disease|Huntington's]], and [[Lupus]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rusinyak|first1=Daniel E.|title=Neurologic manifestations of chronic methamphetamine abuse|journal=Neurologic Clinics|date=2011|volume=29|issue=3|pages=641\u2013655|doi=10.1016/j.ncl.2011.05.004|pmc=3148451|accessdate=|pmid=21803215}}</ref>  Long-term use of amphetamines may increase the risk of [[Parkinson's disease|Parkinson's disease (PD)]]:  in one [[retrospective study]] with over 40,000 participants it was concluded that amphetamine abusers generally had a 200% higher chance of developing PD versus those with no history of abuse; the risk was much higher in women, almost 400%.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hanson|first1=Glen R.|last2=Fleckenstein|first2=Annette E.|last3=Curtin|first3=Kare|title=Dependence on amphetamines increases Parkinson's disease: Effect of gender|journal=Drug and Alcohol Dependence|date=January 1, 2015|volume=146|pages=e134\u2013e135|doi=10.1016/j.drugalcdep.2014.09.284|url=http://www.drugandalcoholdependence.com/article/S0376-8716(14)01346-5/fulltext|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref>  There remains some controversy as of 2017.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kish|first1=Stephen J.|last2=Boileau|first2=Isabelle|last3=Callaghan|first3=Russell C.|last4=Tong|first4=Junchao|title=Brain dopamine neurone 'damage': methamphetamine users vs. Parkinson's disease \u2013 a critical assessment of the evidence|journal=European Journal of Neuroscience|date=2017|volume=45|issue=1|pages=58\u201366|doi=10.1111/ejn.13363|pmid=27519465|pmc=5209286}}</ref>\n\n[[Levodopa-induced dyskinesia]] (LID) is evident in patients with Parkinson's disease who have been on [[levodopa]] ({{L-DOPA}}) for prolonged periods of time. LID commonly first appears in the foot, on the most affected side of the body. There are three main types that can be classified on the basis of their course and clinical presentation following an oral dose of {{L-DOPA}}:<ref name=\"Fabbrini\"/><ref name=\"Thanvi\"/>\n\n* '''Off-period dystonia''' \u2013 correlated to the [[akinesia]] that occurs before the full effect of {{L-DOPA}} sets in, when the plasma levels of {{L-DOPA}} are low. In general, it occurs as painful spasms in the foot. Patients respond to {{L-DOPA}} therapy.<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/>\n* '''Diphasic dyskinesia''' \u2013 occurs when [[blood plasma|plasma]] L-DOPA levels are rising or falling. This form occurs primarily in the lower limbs (though they can happen elsewhere) and is usually [[dystonic]] (characterized by apparent rigidity within muscles or groups thereof) or [[wikt:ballistic|ballistic]] (characterized by involuntary movement of muscles) and will not respond to {{L-DOPA}} dosage reductions.<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/>\n* '''Peak-dose dyskinesia''' \u2013 the most common form of levodopa-induced dyskinesia; it correlates with the plateau {{L-DOPA}} plasma level. This type usually involves the upper limbs more (but could also affect the head, trunk and respiratory muscles), is choreic (of chorea), and less disabling. Patients will respond to {{L-DOPA}} reduction but may be accompanied by deterioration of [[parkinsonism]].<ref name=Fabbrini/><ref name=Thanvi/> Peak-dose L-DOPA-induced dyskinesia has {{As of|2013|07|alt=recently}} been suggested to be associated with cortical dysregulation of dopamine signaling.<ref name=\"Tamte\"/>\n\n===Chronic or tardive===\nLate-onset dyskinesia, also known as [[tardive dyskinesia]], occurs after long-term treatment with an [[antipsychotic]] drug such as [[haloperidol]] (Haldol) or [[amoxapine]] (Asendin). The symptoms include tremors and writhing movements of the body and limbs, and abnormal movements in the face, mouth, and tongue{{spaced ndash}} including involuntary lip smacking, repetitive pouting of the lips, and tongue protrusions.{{sfn|Healy|2008|p=30\u201331}}\n\n[[Rabbit syndrome]] is another type of chronic dyskinesia, while [[orofacial dyskinesia]] may be related to persistent replication of [[Herpes simplex virus type 1]].<ref name=\"Gonazales\" />\n\n===Non-motor===\nTwo other types, [[primary ciliary dyskinesia]] and [[biliary dyskinesia]], are caused by specific kinds of ineffective movement of the body, and are not [[movement disorder]]s.\n\n==See also==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Akathisia]]\n* [[Akinesia]]\n* [[Dopamine]]\n* [[Hemiballismus]]\n* [[Management of Parkinson's disease#Medication|Medication Management of Parkinson's disease]]\n* [[Paroxysmal dyskinesia]]\n* [[Psychosis]]\n* [[Schizophrenia]]\n* [[Serotonin]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\"Fabbrini\">\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Fabbrini G, Brotchie JM, Grandas F, Nomoto M, Goetz CG |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesias |journal=Movement Disorders Society |date=April 2007 |volume=22 |issue=10 |pages=1379\u201389 |doi=10.1002/mds.21475 |pmid=17427940}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Tamte\">\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Halje P, Tamt\u00e8 M, Richter U, Mohammed M, Cenci MA, Petersson P |date=November 2012 |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesia is strongly associated with resonant cortical oscillations |journal=Journal of Neuroscience |volume=32 |issue=47 |pages=16541\u201351 |doi=10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3047-12.2012 |pmid=23175810 |pmc=6621755 |url=http://www.jneurosci.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=23175810 |accessdate=30 November 2013}} {{open access}} {{link note|note=full free text}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Thanvi>\n{{cite journal |vauthors=Thanvi B, Lo N, Robinson T |title=Levodopa-induced dyskinesia in Parkinson's disease: clinical features, pathogenesis, prevention and treatment |journal=Postgraduate Medical Journal |date=June 2007 |volume=83 |issue=980 |pages=384\u201388 |doi=10.1136/pgmj.2006.054759 |pmid=17551069 |pmc=2600052}} {{open access}} {{link note|note=full free text}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Gonazales\">\n{{cite journal |title=Postherpes simplex type 1 neuralgia simulating postherpetic neuralgia |journal=J Pain Symptom Manage |date=July 1992 |volume=7 |issue=5 |pages=320\u20133 |pmid=1624816 |author=Gonzales GR |doi=10.1016/0885-3924(92)90065-p}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==Works cited==\n* {{cite book |author=David Healy |title=Psychiatric Drugs Explained |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ikTJViYMPIEC |accessdate=16 December 2010 |date=3 December 2008 |publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences |isbn=978-0-7020-2997-4}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = 17912 \n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|G|24|9|g|20}} \n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|333.8}} \n|   ICDO           = \n|   OMIM           = \n|   MedlinePlus    = \n|   eMedicineSubj  = \n|   eMedicineTopic = \n|   MeshID         = D020820 \n}}\n{{CNS diseases of the nervous system}}\n{{Nervous and musculoskeletal system symptoms and signs}}\n\n[[Category:Symptoms and signs: Nervous system]]\n[[Category:Parkinson's disease]]\n[[Category:Neurological disorders]]\n[[Category:Extrapyramidal and movement disorders]]\n", "name_user": "Dismanet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding new medical resources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dyskinesia"}
{"title_page": "Kutri", "text_new": "{{Cleanup|reason=reorganise image|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    =Kutri \n| other_name              = \u0915\u0941\u091f\u0930\u0940\n| settlement_type         = Village \n| pushpin_map             = India Bihar#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = left\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Bihar]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of regions of India|Region]]\n| subdivision_type3       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name3       = [[Nawada district|Nawada]]\n| government_type         = [[Panchayati raj (India)]]\n| governing_body          = [[Gram panchayat]] \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Bihar, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|25.023060|N|85.602250|E|display=inline,title}}\n| population_total        = 5445<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/1035_PART_B_DCHB_NAWADA.pdf |title= Nawada District Census Handbook Page No. 3 for Population and Page No. 76 for Village Code |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = Postal Index Number \n| postal_code             = 805130<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nawada.nic.in/std-pin-codes/ |title= Postal Code (PIN) and STD Code |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 06325<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nawada.nic.in/std-pin-codes/ |title= Postal Code (PIN) and STD Code |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n| registration_plate      = BR-27-XXXX\n| website                 = {{URL|nawada.nic.in}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n[[Kutri]] Village with Census of [[India]] Village-code 257586 is located in [[Warisaliganj]] Block of [[Nawada district]] in [[Bihar]], [[India]]. It is one of the historical village amongst 80 villages of [[Warisaliganj]] Block of [[Nawada district]]. According to the government records, Kutri village has 842 houses spread in geographical areas of 368 hectares. It is situated 5 km away from [[Warisaliganj]] Block and 22km away from [[Nawada]]. As of 2009, Kutri village is also a [[gram Panchayat]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://nawada.nic.in/village-panchayats/ |title= Details of Blocks and Villages of Nawada District |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Kutri Gram Panchayat== \n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cdn.s3waas.gov.in/s3a4f23670e1833f3fdb077ca70bbd5d66/uploads/2018/03/2018030651.pdf |title= Panchayat and Village Details of Nawada|publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\nKutri Panchayat consists of following villages:\n*'''Kutri'''\n**[[Naromurar]]\n**Khirbhojna\n**Rampur\n\nKutri village has 3 sub villages, [[Naromurar]], Khirbhojna, Rampur, Tullapur, & Masankhama. Kutri & [[Naromurar]] inhabitants are [[Bhumihar]] [[Brahmins]] and [[Maithil Brahmins]].{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Kutri Village Panorma View.jpg|thumb|center|Panorama View of Kutri.]]\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Village Glimpses\n|align=center\n|File:Gardening near pond.jpg\n |alt1=Gardening Near Pond\n |Gardening Near Pond\n|File:Pond scene.jpg\n |alt2=Pond Beautification\n |Pond Beautification\n|File:Pond Glimpse.jpg\n |alt3=Distant view of Shivala at Pond\n |Distant view of Shivala at Pond\n|File:Pond Photo.jpg\n |alt4=Pond Glimpse\n |Pond Glimpse\n}}\n\n==Culture==\n\n\n\n\n[[File:Kusti.jpg |thumb|left|Kushti at Kutri.]] [[File:Kutri Kusti.jpg |thumb|right|Kushti at Kutri.]]\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=Cultural depictions of Kutri Village\n|align=center\n|File:Kusti photo