condary_school.php |title= Higher Secondary School List SL. No. 64 |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}</ref>\n{{Gallery\n|title=Schools of Kutri Village\n|align=center\n|File:School at Kutri-Nawada.jpg\n |alt1=Middle School at Kutri\n |Middle School at Kutri\n|File:School at Kutri.jpg\n |alt2=High School at Kutri\n |High School at Kutri\n}}\nEducation is the mirror of society civilization & its upbringings. Being [[Magadha Empire]] village, Kutri has witnessed [[vedic]] education and judiciary system in the ancient times. [[Nalanda University]] - an educational hub of India is situated near Kutri village. During the [[British Raj]], School education was initiated in this village with the establishment of Middle School Kutri in the north of the village in 1900\u2019s. Late Siya Saran Singh \u2013 a teacher of Kochgaon village played a pivotal role in proliferating education in Kutri. With the support of Harvansh Kumari alias (Parvati Kumari) a primary school of 3 rooms was constructed during [[Zamindari]] system. Later on, with awareness of  educational  & its importance, school was extended to Middle school up to class7. After [[Indian independence]], Kutri villagers used to go nearby school for high school education i.e. BK Sahoo High School at [[Warisaliganj]].  In 1970\u2019s there were urgent need felt by villagers to improve educational institution in the village for higher secondary education and it was finally decided in Oct 1972 during [[Durga Puja]] Festival that a high school is urgently needed in the proximity of the village. This need was further strengthened with demand of  improving literacy & education among girls. For girls, it was difficult to get higher education due to unavailability of high school in near by locations. At that time, President Late Bhishundeo Singh, Secretary Late Girijanandan Sharma, Treasurer Late Sunder Sharma, Auditor Parasnath Singh formed a committee with some nominated members Such as Sh. Umesh Chandra Sinha, Sh. Ram Lakhan Sharma, Sh. Kushewshar Singh, Late Bharat Singh, Late Rajpati Singh, Late Ramchandra Singh (Chaubhaiya) became active members for high school establishment. Role of president & secretary were immense to get land for the School and subscription or donation amount was offered by all members and many villagers. Considering education an urgent need, members of Natya Kala Parishad, Kutri initiated school foundation for higher education in the south of the village and a foundation stone of  high school was kept by the first district Magistrate of Nawada Shri Narendra Pal Singh on 5th Feb 1973 on the eve of Saraswati Puja. Surprisingly, 5th Feb was the birthday of Sh. Narendrapal Singh (then DM) and when invitation for foundation stone of school was given by Sh. Ram Lakhan Sharma, he accepted this request happily and was ready to support this noble work in all the way. Late Kushewshar Singh became the first Headmaster of Kutri high school and some unemployed villagers at that time used to teach there. Successor headmaster late Ram Naresh Singh put great effort to get uphill task of permanent high school approval from the government authority. In doing so Late Bandi Shankar Singh ([[MLA]], [[Warisaliganj]]), the son of first Chief minister of [[Bihar]] supported very well. In Dec. 1978, Kutri High school became govt approved high school now it is inter high school (10+2). Apart from, this, there was some coaching classes was run privately to bring better education in the village.  The unforgettable name of Late Haridwar Singh was one of them who privately run coaching cum school at late Shyam nandan Pathak banglow. He was very disciplined teacher and kept strong foundation of English literature & Mathematics in the students.  At present there is one middle school & one inter high school in our village where students from nearby villages even from Naromurar, Gorapar, Lohrajpur, Paingari etc. are coming for the education along with our village students. Thus we can say, that our forefathers had strategic vision towards education.\nIn late 1990,s & early 2000\u2019s, a group of villagers Dr. Amit Kumar, Prof.(Dr.) Baliram Pd Singh & Sh  Baliram Sharma understood the difficulties of students to get job oriented education and collected Rs 1100 (rupees eleven hundred only) each to initiate refresher classes for the students with the participation of learned & responsible villagers, such as late Jata Shankar Pathak Ji and many unemployed villagers at that time used to take classes to strengthen basics and to motivate students to face tough competition. Once again in 2020\u2019s Villagers who are in the job and business but out of village at present once again felt the need of the education, and thought that talent is everywhere and we need to up bring them through motivation & creating quiz & competition classes amongst students  to nourish them self dependant citizen of the country. In this direction, a [[WhatsApp]] group i.e. Kutri Residents Group initiated spread of education thought with the support of Maa kali Sewa Sansthan Kutri (Maa Kali Sewa Siksha Sansthan) and conducted [[Quiz]] competition amongst student of different classes to bring competition  amongst students and to understand importance of education under the shadow of Mr. Rupesh Kumar, Umakant, Anjani Kumar, Daya Shankar  who dedicated himself as educationists & motivators from their busy schedule to make it successful. From WhatsApp group, Dr. Amit Kumar. Rakesh Kumar, Mukesh Kumar Singh, Rupesh Kumar, Umakant, Prof. Baliram, sanjeev, Sonu etc took lead to move forward this education awareness under the supervision of Maa Kali Sewa Sanstahan President Shri Ram Avtar Sharma, Secretary, Shri Ram Lakhan Sharma & Treasurer Shri Rajendra Singh. Some of the villagers also contributed financially to support this initiative. MAA KALI SEWA SANSTHAN took active participation in opening saving account and contributed morally as well as financially to uplift poor students.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Villages in Bihar]] \n* [[Nawada District]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://nawada.nic.in |title=Official District Website |publisher= |date= |accessdate=}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Nawada district]]\n", "name_user": "DrAmitKSharma", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCulture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kutri"}
{"title_page": "Lou Handman", "text_new": "'''Lou Handman''' (September 10, 1894 in [[New York City]] &ndash; December 9, 1956 in [[Flushing, New York]]) was a [[composer]]. In his early career toured in [[vaudeville]] shows in [[Australia]] and [[New York City]]. Handman worked closely with [[Roy Turk]]. They went on to make such chart-topping hits as:\n*\"[[Are You Lonesome Tonight? (song)|Are You Lonesome Tonight]]\"\n*\"It's All the Same to Me\"\n*\"My Sweetie Went Away\" - a popular song in 1923 with versions by [[Billy Murray (singer)|Billy Murray]] & Ed Smalle, and by [[Dolly Kay]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954 |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |page=556}}</ref>\n*\"One Night of Love\"\n*\"Two Ton Tessie\"\n*\"You've Got Those Wanna Go Back Again Blues\"\n*\"I'm Gonna Charleston Back to Charleston\"\n*\"Me and the Moon\"\n\nOther hits were:\n*\"Give Me a Smile and a Kiss\"\n*\"I Can't Get the One I Want\"\n*\"What Good Would it Do?\"\n*\"Is My Baby Blue Tonight?\"\n*\"No Nothing\"\n*\"Was it Rain?\"\n*\"Don't Ever Change\"\n*\"Baby Me\"\n*\"Puddin' Head Jones\"\n*\"Blue (And Broken Hearted)\" - a hit for [[Marion Harris]] in 1923.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954 |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |page=197}}</ref>\n\nHandman was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1975.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*[http://songwritershalloffame.org/exhibit_home_page.asp?exhibitId=221 Songwriters Hall of Fame]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Handman, Lou}}\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n\n\n{{US-composer-19thC-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Lou Handman''' (September 10, 1894 in [[New York City]] &ndash; December 9, 1956 in [[Flushing, New York]]) was a [[composer]]. In his early career toured in [[vaudeville]] shows in [[Australia]] and [[New York City]]. Handman worked closely with [[Roy Turk]]. They went on to make such chart-topping hits as:\n*\"[[Are You Lonesome Tonight? (song)|Are You Lonesome Tonight]]\"\n*\"It's All the Same to Me\"\n*\"My Sweetie Went Away\" - a popular song in 1923 with versions by [[Billy Murray (singer)|Billy Murray]] & Ed Smalle, and by [[Dolly Kay]]. <ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954 |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |page=556}}</ref>\n*\"One Night of Love\"\n*\"Two Ton Tessie\"\n*\"You've Got Those Wanna Go Back Again Blues\"\n*\"I'm Gonna Charleston Back to Charleston\"\n*\"Me and the Moon\"\n\nOther hits were:\n*\"Give Me a Smile and a Kiss\"\n*\"I Can't Get the One I Want\"\n*\"What Good Would it Do?\"\n*\"Is My Baby Blue Tonight?\"\n*\"No Nothing\"\n*\"Was it Rain?\"\n*\"Don't Ever Change\"\n*\"Baby Me\"\n*\"Puddin' Head Jones\"\n*\"Blue (And Broken Hearted)\" - a hit for [[Marion Harris]] in 1923.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Whitburn |first1=Joel |title=Joel Whitburn's Pop Memories 1890-1954 |date=1986 |publisher=Record Research Inc. |location=Menomonee Falls, Wisconsin |isbn=0-89820-083-0 |page=197}}</ref>\n\nHandman was inducted into the [[Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1975.\n\n==References==\n*[http://songwritershalloffame.org/exhibit_home_page.asp?exhibitId=221 Songwriters Hall of Fame]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Handman, Lou}}\n[[Category:Jewish American songwriters]]\n[[Category:1894 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n\n\n{{US-composer-19thC-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lou_Handman"}
{"title_page": "Crystal Palace Bowl", "text_new": "[[File:Edited IRAL.jpg|thumb|Crystal Palace Bowl - Ian Ritchie Architects, 1997]]\n\n[[Crystal Palace Bowl]] is an iconic South London venue, with 60 years of live music heritage and a legacy as an outdoor performance venue stretching back over a century. It has a unique sculptural permanent stage designed by [[Ian Ritchie Architects]], which was nominated for the prestigious [[RIBA Stirling Prize]] and is positioned in a natural amphitheatre capable of holding up to 15,000 people, with the stage facing an ornamental lake. It is located within the historic and Grade II* listed [[Crystal Palace Park]] in the [[London Borough of Bromley]]\n\nFrom 1961 it hosted regular classical music performances by the likes of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]. From 1971 to the early 1990s the Bowl saw some of the most popular musical acts in the world across rock, pop, punk, blues, jazz, roots and reggae play the \u2018Garden Party\u2019 festivals and later [[Greater London Council]] organised events.\nNotable concerts included those by [[Pink Floyd]], [[Bob Marley]], [[Elton John]], [[The Beach Boys]], [[Lou Reed]], [[The Cure]] and [[The Pixies]].\n\nThe Bowl has been inactive as a music venue for several years and the stage has fallen into a state of disrepair, but as of March 2020 [[London Borough of Bromley]] Council are working with a local action group to find \u201ccreative and community-minded business proposals to reactivate the cherished concert platform\u201d<ref>https://www.bromley.gov.uk/press/article/1572/creative_proposals_wanted_for_the_future_of_the_concert_platform</ref>.\n\n==Early History==\n\nFollowing the [[Great Exhibition]] of 1851, [[The Crystal Palace]] was relocated from Hyde Park to Sydenham and 200 acres of surrounding land was extensively re-landscaped by original architect Joseph Paxton, creating a spectacular Victorian pleasure ground.\nThe North West corner of the grounds (todays [[Crystal Palace Park]]) was an area initially used for archery demonstrations and known as the \u2018English Garden Landscape\u2019, described thus: \u2018On a beautiful slope bordered by trees is the archery ground, where targets are fixed at various distances. Nearby is [a] small piece of water...and beside it a beautiful grove of trees forming a pleasant summer shade\u2019.\n\nThe sloping topography of the area lent itself to large gatherings, from the 1880s it was used for regular controlled balloon ascents in front of enormous crowds <ref> https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32645536/balloon-ascent-at-crystal-palace-august/</ref>. In 1884 a \u2018Venetian Fete\u2019 was inaugurated, illuminating the English Garden Landscape to spectacular effect with a display of 15,000 oil lamps dotted around the grounds and 2,000 coloured Chinese Lanterns suspended from the trees. The small lake was decorated with a series of semi-circles, floating on the surface and gradually diminishing in size,  their reflections in the water giving the appearance of rings of light stretching into the distance. The Venetian Fete illuminations were choreographed by the pyrotechnic specialists [[Brocks Fireworks|Brocks]], well known for their firework displays at the Palace.\n\n==Pageant of London==\n\n[[File:Pageant Ground.jpg|thumb|1911 'Pageant of London' grounds at Crystal Palace]]\n\nFor the 1911 [[Festival of Empire]] held at Crystal Palace, the central attraction was a \u2018Pageant of London\u2019, sited in the natural amphitheatre of the English Garden Landscape.\nMasterminded by [[Frank Lascelles (pageant master)|Frank Lascelles]], this was a hugely ambitious theatrical spectacle of historical re-enactments in several acts, with a cast of 15,000 performers telling the story of London, Britain and the Empire. It was sound-tracked by an original and patriotic score written by 17 native composers, amongst them [[Edward Elgar]] and [[Gustav Holst]].\n\nA temporary grandstand accommodating up to 10,000 spectators was constructed and 120 performances were given between June and September 1911, with over 1 million visitors traveling from across the country to see the Pageant. A contemporary review of the Pageant by [[The Times]] concluded \u2018It would be difficult to conceive of a finer effect than was given by the mingling of theatrical art with the natural beauty of the arena'<ref> Collated in \u2018Festival Of Empire\u2019, Times, 19 June 1911, 20 and \u2018Pageant Of London\u2019, Times, 15 June 1911, 12.</ref>\n\nThe event was the first use of this area of the grounds as a large scale public performance venue and in terms of historical significance, it was \"undoubtedly the largest and most ambitious pageant of the Edwardian period, if not the whole twentieth century, [and] it stands alone as a seminal moment in the growing popular appeal of pageantry\"<ref>http://www.historicalpageants.ac.uk/pageants/1305/</ref>\n\n==Music in the Open Air==\n\n[[File:CP Amphitheatre 1955 Plan.jpg|thumb|Crystal Palace Park acoustic shell stage proposal, 1955 masterplan.]]\n\nAfter the huge success of the 1951 Festival of Britain on London\u2019s [[South Bank]] (directly inspired by the 1851 [[Great Exhibition]] at Crystal Palace) and in the spirit of post-war optimism, an ambitious new masterplan was developed in 1955 for the scarred and dilapidated park, which had been closed to the public since the destruction of the Palace by fire in 1936. This included a national exhibition and sports centre, a 160ft high observation tower and an acoustic shell stage for open air concerts<ref> http://www.crystalpalacefoundation.org.uk/history/crystal-palace-timeline-1937-2005</ref>\n\n[[File:Proms 60's.jpg|thumb|left|London Philharmonic Orchestra at Crystal Palace Bowl, 1962 (Photo by Allan Hailstone \u00a9)]]\n\nSited in the small lake and facing the natural amphitheatre of the area formerly known as \u2018English Garden Landscape\u2019, an elegant concrete and steel shell stage design was proposed but never built. However preparatory work was soon begun on a temporary stage that would enable open air concerts in the park.\n\nIn June 1961, the new Crystal Palace Concert Bowl opened with a performance conducted by Antal Dorati<ref> https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/the-inaugural-concert-orchestra-conducted-by-antal-dorati-at-the-crystal-palace-bowl-1464079a</ref>, resuming a musical tradition at the Palace that stretched back more than a century to the great [[Handel]] Festivals and pre-war Brass Band Championships.\nThe \u2018Music in the Open Air\u2019 and 'Proms in the Park' classic concerts grew in popularity throughout the 1960s and became a popular annual fixture, continuing in various forms and with differing orchestras for over 45 years until circa 2007. \n\n== Garden Party Festivals==\n\n[[File:1971_-_Garden_Party_I_Poster_(2).jpg#file|thumb|Pink Floyd, Crystal Palace Garden Party 1971]]\n\nAfter the first decade of solely classical music at Crystal Palace Bowl, the [[Greater London Council]] were persuaded by young promoters [[Harvey Goldsmith]] and Michael Alfondary, to allow large scale rock and pop events to be staged at the venue<ref> https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HATDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT115&lpg=PT115&dq=harvey+goldsmith+crystal+palace+garden+party&source=bl&ots=WSi4KS9x5R&sig=ACfU3U1GXYMSSeSJJn68xSxkejc7zzkLPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi0kYG9oMDoAhWIZhUIHQ8XAHw4ChDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=harvey%20goldsmith%20crystal%20palace%20garden%20party&f=false</ref>.\n\nGoldsmith and Alfondary partnered with father and son promoters John and [[Tony Smith]] \u2013 who managed many of the major touring acts at the time -  together launching \u2018Crystal Palace Garden Party\u2019 with an inaugural event in May 1971. Coming quickly on the heels of the new large multi-day pop festivals in mostly rural locations; like [[The Isle of Wight Festival]](1968), [[Woodstock]](1969) and [[Glastonbury Festival]](1970), Crystal Palace Garden Party pioneered a different formula \u2013 the more modest sized, semi-urban one day festival.\n\n[[File:Beach Boys 1972.jpg|thumb|left|Beach Boys at Crystal Palace Garden Party, 1972 (Photo by Michael Putland \u00a9)]]\n\nInitially running twice annually, the Garden Party events quickly gained a reputation for their eclectic line-ups and over excitable members of the audience venturing into the lake for a closer view of the stage. The experimental format of events and occasional madcap incidences also feature regularly in recollections. At one event in 1972, [[The Who]] drummer Keith Moon acted as compere; after arriving via helicopter and reaching the stage by hovercraft, he proceeded to take a rowing boat on the lake and, while dressed as a pirate, served tea and cake to people in the crowd closest to the waters edge<ref> https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2t1T3Jywu0MC&pg=PT376&lpg=PT376&dq=keith+moon+crystal+palace+bowl+helicopter&source=bl&ots=RGptzl94dU&sig=ACfU3U0rH-09NTHJcMVwexvl7UG58uLb2A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi9j82WvcDoAhU4UxUIHUbdCgYQ6AEwC3oECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=keith%20moon%20crystal%20palace%20bowl%20helicopter&f=false</ref>.\n\nOn other occasions, the close proximity of the television transmitter in the park caused interference with the PA system, with music inadvertently interrupted by [[Test Match Special]] radio commentary from an England V Australia cricket match <ref> https://accessaa.co.uk/how-golden-era-pioneer-harvey-goldsmith-has-stayed-on-the-cutting-edge/</ref>.\n\nOver 10 years many of the defining guitarists of the era would appear at Crystal Palace, including [[Eric Clapton]], [[Carlos Santana]], [[David Gilmour]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Rory Gallagher]], [[Ronnie Wood]], [[Mick Taylor]] and [[John McLaughlin (musician)|John McLaughlin]]. \n\nThe Garden Party events reached a climax in the summer of 1980, when [[Bob Marley]] played to a record breaking crowd at the Bowl; his last concert in London and one of the final few performances before his death the following year. From 1981, organisation of events in London parks was taken over by the GLC and under new Labour leader of the council [[Ken Livingston]], would take on a noticeably more political tone. \n\nOn the day of the Royal Wedding between Prince Charles and Diana in 1981, the 'It's Only Rock 'n' Royal' event was hosted at the Bowl. Headlined by [[Ian Dury]], the press christened this a 'Republican rock fest', while Livingstone retorted \"not everyone will want to sit square-eyed in front of a television all day \u2013 It's part of our programme of public benefit under socialism\u201d.\nIn 1983 [[Curtis Mayfield]] headlined the GLC Peace Picnic \u2018Blues in the Bowl\u2019, while in 1984 \u2018London Against Racism\u2019 and a \u2018Free Nelson Mandela\u2019 Benefit concert brought world music in the form of [[Jimmy Cliff]], [[Hugh Masakela]], [[Gil Scot Heron]] and [[Segun Adewale]]. In 1985 an Anti-Heroin benefit concert organised by [[Pete Townsend]] featured the odd pairing of [[Hawkwind]] followed by forces sweetheart [[Dame Vera Lynn]].\n[[File:19840728_JIMMY_CLIFF@London(0861-24).jpg|thumb|Jimmy Cliff at the Free Nelson Mandela Benefit, Crystal Palace Bowl 1984 (Photo by Masataka Ishida \u00a9)]]\nA brief cessation in events at the Bowl followed the abolition of the GLC in 1986. They resumed in 1990 at an event headlined by [[The Cure]] and a brief revival of the \u2018Garden Party\u2019 moniker. In 1991 [[The Pixies]] played their biggest ever UK show, topping a bill of popular indie bands, while Blues and American music festivals brought roots legends like [[Buddy Guy]], [[John Lee Hooker]], [[Ry Cooder]] and [[Emmylou Harris]] to South London. The ageing temporary stage at the Bowl closed in 1994/95 in preparation for the construction of a new permanent stage and a shift towards smaller emerging acts and classical music.\n\nElsewhere in the park, live music continued over the next few years on much larger scale. With the boom in the acid house and dance music scene, the [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre]] hosted \u2018Elevation and Reincarnation\u2019 from 1991-1994, London\u2019s largest indoors legal [[raves]]. Capital FM \u2018Party at the Palace\u2019 Roadshows on the park terraces gave early outings to a pre-fame [[Take That]] and [[East 17]]. Meanwhile the athletics stadium at the Sports Centre, with capacity for up to 40,000 people, welcomed the likes of [[Depeche Mode]], [[Paul Weller]], and [[Santana (band)|Santana]] in the 1990s and early 2000s.\n\nIn 2002 the [[Sex Pistols]] reunited to celebrate their Jubilee (coinciding with her Majesty the Queen) with a huge \u2018Pistols at the Palace\u2019 day festival. [[Bruce Springsteen and the E-Street Band]] played a bank holiday double-header in 2003 on their \u2018The Rising\u2019 reunion tour, while a pair of [[Coldplay]] shows in 2005 marked the final big gigs at Crystal Palace to date.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:tmrX5wnA.jpg#file|thumb|Crystal Palace concert platform and lake - Ian Ritchie Architects, 1997]]\n\nIn 1996 an architectural competition was by held by [[London Borough of Bromley]] and [[Arts Council England]], to design a new permanent stage in the park. [[Ian Ritchie Architects]] won with a proposal for a  \u201csimple structure causing minimal disturbance\u201d <ref>https://www.ianritchiearchitects.co.uk/projects/concert_stand/</ref> to the rich and complex Paxton landscape.\n\nThe sculptural form was inspired by artists like [[Richard Serra]] and architects like [[John Winter (architect)|John Winter]] in its use of a single material and a continuous surface, namely the self-weathering pre-rusted [[Corten Steel]]; it was of the first public buildings in the UK to use the material for external cladding. The outward appearance of the deep red oxidised steel drew inspiration from the earthy colours of the soil and reflections of the sky in the ornamental lake in front of the stage area, aiming to produce a greater harmony between structure and the beauty of surrounding landscape.\n[[File:DennisGilbert Aug1997 (9).jpg#file|thumb|left|August 1997, Crystal Palace Concert (Photo by Dennis Gilbert \u00a9)]]\n\n\nA generously proportioned 25 metre wide by 15 metre deep stage could accommodate a full 120 piece orchestra, while the acoustic canopy projects over the stage and soars to 11.34 metres high, cantilevered at an angle of 40 degrees. The structure also boasted the world's first computer controlled outdoor active acoustic system, designed by Paul Gilleron<ref> https://www.gsacoustics.org/</ref>. This enabled the stage acoustics to be tuned as required by the performers; the canopy contains a total of 46 speakers, with two freestanding columns either side of the stage designed to house speakers and the amplification system<ref>http://www.galinsky.com/buildings/crystalpalacepark/</ref>.\n\nThe new stage opened in August 1997 with a performance by [[Evelyn Glennie]], in 1998 it was nominated for the [[RIBA Stirling Prize]], while also winning the [[Royal Fine Arts Commission]] Building of the Year Award, a [[Civic Trust Award]] and the 'Excellence in Design' award from the [[American Institute of Architects]].\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.ianritchiearchitects.co.uk/projects/concert_stand/index.htm Ian Ritchie Architects]\n[http://www.galinsky.com/buildings/crystalpalacepark/index.htm Crystal Palace Concert Bowl]\n\n{{coord|51.4240|-0.0691|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Music venues in London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace, London]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Edited IRAL.jpg|thumb|Crystal Palace Bowl - Ian Ritchie Architects, 1997]]\n\n[[Crystal Palace Bowl]] is an iconic South London venue, with 60 years of live music heritage and a legacy as an outdoor performance venue stretching back over a century. It has a unique sculptural permanent stage designed by [[Ian Ritchie Architects]], which was nominated for the prestigious [[RIBA Stirling Prize]] and is positioned in a natural amphitheatre capable of holding up to 15,000 people, with the stage facing an ornamental lake. It is located within the historic and Grade II* listed [[Crystal Palace Park]] in the [[London Borough of Bromley]]\n\nFrom 1961 it hosted regular classical music performances by the likes of the [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and [[London Philharmonic Orchestra]]. From 1971 to the early 1990\u2019s the Bowl saw some of the most popular musical acts in the world across rock, pop, punk, blues, jazz, roots and reggae play the \u2018Garden Party\u2019 festivals and later [[Greater London Council]] organised events.\nNotable concerts included those by [[Pink Floyd]], [[Bob Marley]], [[Elton John]], [[The Beach Boys]], [[Lou Reed]], [[The Cure]] and [[The Pixies]].\n\nThe Bowl has been inactive as a music venue for several years and the stage has fallen into a state of disrepair, but as of March 2020 [[London Borough of Bromley]] Council are working with a local action group to find \u201ccreative and community-minded business proposals to reactivate the cherished concert platform\u201d<ref>https://www.bromley.gov.uk/press/article/1572/creative_proposals_wanted_for_the_future_of_the_concert_platform</ref>.\n\n==Early History==\n\nFollowing the [[Great Exhibition]] of 1851, [[The Crystal Palace]] was relocated from Hyde Park to Sydenham and 200 acres of surrounding land was extensively re-landscaped by original architect Joseph Paxton, creating a spectacular Victorian pleasure ground.\nThe North West corner of the grounds (todays [[Crystal Palace Park]]) was an area initially used for archery demonstrations and known as the \u2018English Garden Landscape\u2019, described thus: \u2018On a beautiful slope bordered by trees is the archery ground, where targets are fixed at various distances. Nearby is [a] small piece of water...and beside it a beautiful grove of trees forming a pleasant summer shade\u2019.\n\nThe sloping topography of the area lent itself to large gatherings, from the 1880\u2019s it was used for regular controlled balloon ascents in front of enormous crowds <ref> https://www.newspapers.com/clip/32645536/balloon-ascent-at-crystal-palace-august/</ref>. In 1884 a \u2018Venetian Fete\u2019 was inaugurated, illuminating the English Garden Landscape to spectacular effect with a display of 15,000 oil lamps dotted around the grounds and 2,000 coloured Chinese Lanterns suspended from the trees. The small lake was decorated with a series of semi-circles, floating on the surface and gradually diminishing in size,  their reflections in the water giving the appearance of rings of light stretching into the distance. The Venetian Fete illuminations were choreographed by the pyrotechnic specialists [[Brocks Fireworks|Brocks]], well known for their firework displays at the Palace.\n\n==Pageant of London==\n\n[[File:Pageant Ground.jpg|thumb|1911 'Pageant of London' grounds at Crystal Palace]]\n\nFor the 1911 [[Festival of Empire]] held at Crystal Palace, the central attraction was a \u2018Pageant of London\u2019, sited in the natural amphitheatre of the English Garden Landscape.\nMasterminded by [[Frank Lascelles (pageant master)|Frank Lascelles]], this was a hugely ambitious theatrical spectacle of historical re-enactments in several acts, with a cast of 15,000 performers telling the story of London, Britain and the Empire. It was sound-tracked by an original and patriotic score written by 17 native composers, amongst them [[Edward Elgar]] and [[Gustav Holst]].\n\nA temporary grandstand accommodating up to 10,000 spectators was constructed and 120 performances were given between June and September 1911, with over 1 million visitors traveling from across the country to see the Pageant. A contemporary review of the Pageant by [[The Times]] concluded \u2018It would be difficult to conceive of a finer effect than was given by the mingling of theatrical art with the natural beauty of the arena'<ref> Collated in \u2018Festival Of Empire\u2019, Times, 19 June 1911, 20 and \u2018Pageant Of London\u2019, Times, 15 June 1911, 12.</ref>\n\nThe event was the first use of this area of the grounds as a large scale public performance venue and in terms of historical significance, it was \"undoubtedly the largest and most ambitious pageant of the Edwardian period, if not the whole twentieth century, [and] it stands alone as a seminal moment in the growing popular appeal of pageantry\"<ref>http://www.historicalpageants.ac.uk/pageants/1305/</ref>\n\n==Music in the Open Air==\n\n[[File:CP Amphitheatre 1955 Plan.jpg|thumb|Crystal Palace Park acoustic shell stage proposal, 1955 masterplan.]]\n\nAfter the huge success of the 1951 Festival of Britain on London\u2019s [[South Bank]] (directly inspired by the 1851 [[Great Exhibition]] at Crystal Palace) and in the spirit of post-war optimism, an ambitious new masterplan was developed in 1955 for the scarred and dilapidated park, which had been closed to the public since the destruction of the Palace by fire in 1936. This included a national exhibition and sports centre, a 160ft high observation tower and an acoustic shell stage for open air concerts<ref> http://www.crystalpalacefoundation.org.uk/history/crystal-palace-timeline-1937-2005</ref>\n\n[[File:Proms 60's.jpg|thumb|left|London Philharmonic Orchestra at Crystal Palace Bowl, 1962 (Photo by Allan Hailstone \u00a9)]]\n\nSited in the small lake and facing the natural amphitheatre of the area formerly known as \u2018English Garden Landscape\u2019, an elegant concrete and steel shell stage design was proposed but never built. However preparatory work was soon begun on a temporary stage that would enable open air concerts in the park.\n\nIn June 1961, the new Crystal Palace Concert Bowl opened with a performance conducted by Antal Dorati<ref> https://www.shutterstock.com/editorial/image-editorial/the-inaugural-concert-orchestra-conducted-by-antal-dorati-at-the-crystal-palace-bowl-1464079a</ref>, resuming a musical tradition at the Palace that stretched back more than a century to the great [[Handel]] Festivals and pre-war Brass Band Championships.\nThe \u2018Music in the Open Air\u2019 and 'Proms in the Park' classic concerts grew in popularity throughout the 1960\u2019s and became a popular annual fixture, continuing in various forms and with differing orchestras for over 45 years until circa 2007. \n\n== Garden Party Festivals==\n\n[[File:1971_-_Garden_Party_I_Poster_(2).jpg#file|thumb|Pink Floyd, Crystal Palace Garden Party 1971]]\n\nAfter the first decade of solely classical music at Crystal Palace Bowl, the [[Greater London Council]] were persuaded by young promoters [[Harvey Goldsmith]] and Michael Alfondary, to allow large scale rock and pop events to be staged at the venue<ref> https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=HATDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT115&lpg=PT115&dq=harvey+goldsmith+crystal+palace+garden+party&source=bl&ots=WSi4KS9x5R&sig=ACfU3U1GXYMSSeSJJn68xSxkejc7zzkLPg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi0kYG9oMDoAhWIZhUIHQ8XAHw4ChDoATACegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=harvey%20goldsmith%20crystal%20palace%20garden%20party&f=false</ref>.\n\nGoldsmith and Alfondary partnered with father and son promoters John and [[Tony Smith]] \u2013 who managed many of the major touring acts at the time -  together launching \u2018Crystal Palace Garden Party\u2019 with an inaugural event in May 1971. Coming quickly on the heels of the new large multi-day pop festivals in mostly rural locations; like [[The Isle of Wight Festival]](1968), [[Woodstock]](1969) and [[Glastonbury Festival]](1970), Crystal Palace Garden Party pioneered a different formula \u2013 the more modest sized, semi-urban one day festival.\n\n[[File:Beach Boys 1972.jpg|thumb|left|Beach Boys at Crystal Palace Garden Party, 1972 (Photo by Michael Putland \u00a9)]]\n\nInitially running twice annually, the Garden Party events quickly gained a reputation for their eclectic line-ups and over excitable members of the audience venturing into the lake for a closer view of the stage. The experimental format of events and occasional madcap incidences also feature regularly in recollections. At one event in 1972, [[The Who]] drummer Keith Moon acted as compere; after arriving via helicopter and reaching the stage by hovercraft, he proceeded to take a rowing boat on the lake and, while dressed as a pirate, served tea and cake to people in the crowd closest to the waters edge<ref> https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2t1T3Jywu0MC&pg=PT376&lpg=PT376&dq=keith+moon+crystal+palace+bowl+helicopter&source=bl&ots=RGptzl94dU&sig=ACfU3U0rH-09NTHJcMVwexvl7UG58uLb2A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi9j82WvcDoAhU4UxUIHUbdCgYQ6AEwC3oECAsQAQ#v=onepage&q=keith%20moon%20crystal%20palace%20bowl%20helicopter&f=false</ref>.\n\nOn other occasions, the close proximity of the television transmitter in the park caused interference with the PA system, with music inadvertently interrupted by [[Test Match Special]] radio commentary from an England V Australia cricket match <ref> https://accessaa.co.uk/how-golden-era-pioneer-harvey-goldsmith-has-stayed-on-the-cutting-edge/</ref>.\n\nOver 10 years many of the defining guitarists of the era would appear at Crystal Palace, including [[Eric Clapton]], [[Carlos Santana]], [[David Gilmour]], [[Jeff Beck]], [[Rory Gallagher]], [[Ronnie Wood]], [[Mick Taylor]] and [[John McLaughlin (musician)|John McLaughlin]]. \n\nThe Garden Party events reached a climax in the summer of 1980, when [[Bob Marley]] played to a record breaking crowd at the Bowl; his last concert in London and one of the final few performances before his death the following year. From 1981, organisation of events in London parks was taken over by the GLC and under new Labour leader of the council [[Ken Livingston]], would take on a noticeably more political tone. \n\nOn the day of the Royal Wedding between Prince Charles and Diana in 1981, the 'It's Only Rock 'n' Royal' event was hosted at the Bowl. Headlined by [[Ian Dury]], the press christened this a 'Republican rock fest', while Livingstone retorted \"not everyone will want to sit square-eyed in front of a television all day \u2013 It's part of our programme of public benefit under socialism\u201d.\nIn 1983 [[Curtis Mayfield]] headlined the GLC Peace Picnic \u2018Blues in the Bowl\u2019, while in 1984 \u2018London Against Racism\u2019 and a \u2018Free Nelson Mandela\u2019 Benefit concert brought world music in the form of [[Jimmy Cliff]], [[Hugh Masakela]], [[Gil Scot Heron]] and [[Segun Adewale]]. In 1985 an Anti-Heroin benefit concert organised by [[Pete Townsend]] featured the odd pairing of [[Hawkwind]] followed by forces sweetheart [[Dame Vera Lynn]].\n[[File:19840728_JIMMY_CLIFF@London(0861-24).jpg|thumb|Jimmy Cliff at the Free Nelson Mandela Benefit, Crystal Palace Bowl 1984 (Photo by Masataka Ishida \u00a9)]]\nA brief cessation in events at the Bowl followed the abolition of the GLC in 1986. They resumed in 1990 at an event headlined by [[The Cure]] and a brief revival of the \u2018Garden Party\u2019 moniker. In 1991 [[The Pixies]] played their biggest ever UK show, topping a bill of popular indie bands, while Blues and American music festivals brought roots legends like [[Buddy Guy]], [[John Lee Hooker]], [[Ry Cooder]] and [[Emmylou Harris]] to South London. The ageing temporary stage at the Bowl closed in 1994/95 in preparation for the construction of a new permanent stage and a shift towards smaller emerging acts and classical music.\n\nElsewhere in the park, live music continued over the next few years on much larger scale. With the boom in the acid house and dance music scene, the [[Crystal Palace National Sports Centre]] hosted \u2018Elevation and Reincarnation\u2019 from 1991-1994, London\u2019s largest indoors legal [[raves]]. Capital FM \u2018Party at the Palace\u2019 Roadshows on the park terraces gave early outings to a pre-fame [[Take That]] and [[East 17]]. Meanwhile the athletics stadium at the Sports Centre, with capacity for up to 40,000 people, welcomed the likes of [[Depeche Mode]], [[Paul Weller]], and [[Santana (band)|Santana]] in the 1990\u2019s and early 2000\u2019s.\n\nIn 2002 the [[Sex Pistols]] reunited to celebrate their Jubilee (coinciding with her Majesty the Queen) with a huge \u2018Pistols at the Palace\u2019 day festival. [[Bruce Springsteen and the E-Street Band]] played a bank holiday double-header in 2003 on their \u2018The Rising\u2019 reunion tour, while a pair of [[Coldplay]] shows in 2005 marked the final big gigs at Crystal Palace to date.\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:tmrX5wnA.jpg#file|thumb|Crystal Palace concert platform and lake - Ian Ritchie Architects, 1997]]\n\nIn 1996 an architectural competition was by held by [[London Borough of Bromley]] and [[Arts Council England]], to design a new permanent stage in the park. [[Ian Ritchie Architects]] won with a proposal for a  \u201csimple structure causing minimal disturbance\u201d <ref>https://www.ianritchiearchitects.co.uk/projects/concert_stand/</ref> to the rich and complex Paxton landscape.\n\nThe sculptural form was inspired by artists like [[Richard Serra]] and architects like [[John Winter (architect)|John Winter]] in its use of a single material and a continuous surface, namely the self-weathering pre-rusted [[Corten Steel]]; it was of the first public buildings in the UK to use the material for external cladding. The outward appearance of the deep red oxidised steel drew inspiration from the earthy colours of the soil and reflections of the sky in the ornamental lake in front of the stage area, aiming to produce a greater harmony between structure and the beauty of surrounding landscape.\n[[File:DennisGilbert Aug1997 (9).jpg#file|thumb|left|August 1997, Crystal Palace Concert (Photo by Dennis Gilbert \u00a9)]]\n\n\nA generously proportioned 25 metre wide by 15 metre deep stage could accommodate a full 120 piece orchestra, while the acoustic canopy projects over the stage and soars to 11.34 metres high, cantilevered at an angle of 40 degrees. The structure also boasted the world's first computer controlled outdoor active acoustic system, designed by Paul Gilleron<ref> https://www.gsacoustics.org/</ref>. This enabled the stage acoustics to be tuned as required by the performers; the canopy contains a total of 46 speakers, with two freestanding columns either side of the stage designed to house speakers and the amplification system<ref>http://www.galinsky.com/buildings/crystalpalacepark/</ref>.\n\nThe new stage opened in August 1997 with a performance by [[Evelyn Glennie]], in 1998 it was nominated for the [[RIBA Stirling Prize]], while also winning the [[Royal Fine Arts Commission]] Building of the Year Award, a [[Civic Trust Award]] and the 'Excellence in Design' award from the [[American Institute of Architects]].\n\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[https://www.ianritchiearchitects.co.uk/projects/concert_stand/index.htm Ian Ritchie Architects]\n[http://www.galinsky.com/buildings/crystalpalacepark/index.htm Crystal Palace Concert Bowl]\n\n{{coord|51.4240|-0.0691|region:GB_type:landmark|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Music venues in London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the London Borough of Bromley]]\n[[Category:Crystal Palace, London]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_Palace_Bowl"}
{"title_page": "Roseola", "text_new": "{{Short description|Human disease caused by human herpesviruses}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Roseola\n| synonyms        = Exanthema subitum,<ref name=St2014/> roseola infantum,<ref name=St2014/> sixth disease,<ref name=St2014/> baby measles, rose rash of infants, three-day fever\n| image           = Roseola on a 21-month-old girl.jpg\n| caption         = Roseola on a 21-month-old girl\n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = Fever followed by rash<ref name=St2014/>\n| complications   = [[Febrile seizures]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| onset           = Before the age of three<ref name=St2014/>\n| duration        = Few days<ref name=CDC2017/>\n| types           = \n| causes          = ''[[Human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) or ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7)<ref name=St2014/>\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = Typically based on symptoms<ref name=St2014/>\n| differential    = [[Measles]], [[rubella]], [[scarlet fever]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = [[Supportive care]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = Generally good<ref name=St2014/>\n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Roseola''' is an [[infectious disease]] caused by certain types of [[virus]].<ref name=CDC2017>{{cite journal|last1=Campadelli-Fiume|first1=Gabriella|title=Human Herpesvirus 6: An Emerging Pathogen|journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases|volume=5|issue=3|pages=353\u2013366|language=en-us|doi=10.3201/eid0503.990306|pmid=10341172|pmc=2640789|df=|year=1999}}</ref> Most infections occur before the age of three.<ref name=St2014>{{cite journal|last1=Stone|first1=RC|last2=Micali|first2=GA|last3=Schwartz|first3=RA|title=Roseola infantum and its causal human herpesviruses.|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|date=April 2014|volume=53|issue=4|pages=397\u2013403|doi=10.1111/ijd.12310|pmid=24673253}}</ref> Symptoms vary from absent to the classic presentation of a fever of rapid onset followed by a rash.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/> The fever generally lasts for three to five days.<ref name=St2014/> The rash is generally pink and lasts for less than three days.<ref name=St2014/> Complications may include [[febrile seizures]], with serious complications being rare.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/>\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nIt is caused by either ''[[human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) or ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7).<ref name=St2014/> Spread is usually through the [[saliva]] of those who are otherwise healthy.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/> However, it may also spread from the mother to baby during pregnancy.<ref name=St2014/> Diagnosis is typically based on symptoms but can be confirmed with blood tests.<ref name=St2014/> Low numbers of [[white blood cell]]s may also be present.<ref name=St2014/>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nTreatment includes sufficient fluids and medications to treat the fever.<ref name=St2014/> Nearly all people are infected at some point in time.<ref name=CDC2017/> Males and females are affected equally often.<ref name=St2014/> The disease was first described in 1910 while the causal virus was determined in 1988.<ref name=St2014/> The disease may reactivate in those with a [[immunocompromised|weakened immune system]] and may result in significant health problems.<ref name=CDC2017/>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nRoseola typically affects children between six months and two years of age, and begins with a sudden high [[fever]] (39\u201340&nbsp;\u00b0C; 102.2-104&nbsp;\u00b0F). In rare cases, this can cause febrile convulsions (also known as [[febrile seizure]]s or \"fever fits\") due to the sudden rise in body temperature, but in many cases the child appears normal. After a few days the fever subsides, and just as the child appears to be recovering, a red rash appears. This usually begins on the trunk (torso) and then spreads to the arms, legs, and neck. The rash is not itchy and may last 1 to 2 days.<ref>[http://www.webmd.com/skin-problems-and-treatments/tc/roseola-topic-overview ''Roseola \u2013 Topic Overview''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727031317/http://www.webmd.com/skin-problems-and-treatments/tc/roseola-topic-overview |date=2008-07-27 }}, webmd.com</ref> In contrast, a child suffering from [[measles]] would usually appear sicker, with symptoms of [[conjunctivitis]], [[coryza|cold-like symptoms]], and a cough, and their rash would affect the face and last for several days. Liver dysfunction can occur in rare cases.\n\nA small percentage of children acquire HHV-6 with few signs or symptoms of the disease. Exanthema subitum occurs in approximately 30% of children during primary HHV-6 infection.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Zerr | first1 = D. M. | last2 = Meier | first2 = A. S. | last3 = Selke | first3 = S. S. | last4 = Frenkel | first4 = L. M. | last5 = Huang | first5 = M. L. | last6 = Wald | first6 = A. | last7 = Rhoads | first7 = M. P. | last8 = Nguy | first8 = L. | last9 = Bornemann | first9 = R. | last10 = Morrow | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa042207 | first10 = R. A. | last11 = Corey | first11 = L. | title = A Population-Based Study of Primary Human Herpesvirus 6 Infection | journal = New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 352 | issue = 8 | pages = 768\u2013776 | year = 2005 | pmid =  15728809| pmc = }}</ref> Others may show symptoms significant enough that other more serious infections, such as [[meningitis]] or measles should be ruled out. In case of febrile seizures, medical advice can be sought for reassurance. \n\nIn rare cases, HHV-6 can become active in an adult previously infected during childhood and can show signs of [[Infectious mononucleosis|mononucleosis]].<ref name=\"pmid10774474\">{{cite journal |author=Stoeckle MY |title=The spectrum of human herpesvirus 6 infection: from roseola infantum to adult disease |journal=Annu. Rev. Med. |volume=51 |issue= |pages=423\u201330 |year=2000 |pmid=10774474 |doi=10.1146/annurev.med.51.1.423 }}</ref>\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Hhv-6 (1).jpg|thumb|Electron micrograph of HHV-6]]\nRoseola is caused by two human [[herpesvirus]]es, ''[[human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) and ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7), which are sometimes referred to collectively as [[Roseolovirus]]. There are two variants of HHV-6 (HHV-6a and HHV-6b) and studies in the US, Europe, Dubai and Japan have shown that exanthema subitum is caused by HHV-6b. This form of HHV-6 infects over 90% of infants by age 2.\n\n==Prevention==\nThere is no specific [[vaccine]] against or treatment for exanthema subitum, and most children with the disease are not seriously ill.\n\n==Treatment==\nMost cases of HHV-6 infection get better on their own.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tesini|first1=BL|last2=Epstein|first2=LG|last3=Caserta|first3=MT|title=Clinical impact of primary infection with roseoloviruses.|journal=Current Opinion in Virology|date=December 2014|volume=9|pages=91\u20136|pmid=25462439|doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2014.09.013|pmc=4267952}}</ref> If [[encephalitis]] occurs [[ganciclovir]] or [[foscarnet]] may be useful.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ongr\u00e1di|first1=J|last2=Ablashi|first2=DV|last3=Yoshikawa|first3=T|last4=Stercz|first4=B|last5=Ogata|first5=M|title=Roseolovirus-associated encephalitis in immunocompetent and immunocompromised individuals.|journal=Journal of NeuroVirology|date=February 2017|volume=23|issue=1|pages=1\u201319|pmid=27538995|doi=10.1007/s13365-016-0473-0|pmc=5329081}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[John Zahorsky]] MD wrote extensively on this disease in the early 20th century, his first formal presentation was to the St Louis Pediatric society in 1909 where he described 15 young children with the illness. In a JAMA article published on Oct 18, 1913 he noted that \"the name 'Roseola infantilis' had an important place in the medical terminology of writers on skin diseases\" but that descriptions of the disease by previous writers tended to confuse it with many other diseases that produce febrile rashes. In this JAMA article Zahorsky reports on 29 more children with Roseola and notes that the only condition that should seriously be considered in the differential diagnosis is German Measles ([[rubella]]) but notes that the fever of rubella only lasts a few hours whereas the prodromal fever of Roseola lasts three to five days and disappears with the formation of a [[morbilliform]] rash.<ref>John Zahorsky. Roseola Infantum. Journal of the American Medical Association. Oct 18, 1913 pages 1446-1450</ref>\n\n==Names==\n{{More citations needed section|date=November 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Country'''\n|'''Local name (language)'''\n|'''Translated name'''\n|-\n|Belgium\n|Driedagenkoorts (Dutch)<br />Zesde ziekte (Dutch)<br />Ros\u00e9ole (French)\n|\"three-day fever\"<br />\"sixth disease\"<br />-\n|-\n|China (PRC)\n|\u6025\u75b9 (Mandarin) j\u00ed zh\u011bn (pinyin)\n|\"fast rash\"\n|-\n|Czech republic\n|\u0160est\u00e1 nemoc (Czech)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Denmark\n|Tredagsfeber (Danish)\n|\"three day fever\"\n|-\n|Estonia\n|Roseool, kolme p\u00e4eva palavik\n|Roseola/three day fever\n|-\n|Finland\n|Vauvarokko (Finnish)\n|\"baby measles\"\n|-\n|France\n|Ros\u00e9ole\n|\"Roseola\"\n|-\n|Germany\n|Drei-Tage-Fieber (German)\n|\"three-day fever\"\n|-\n|Greece\n|\u0391\u03b9\u03c6\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf \u03b5\u03be\u03ac\u03bd\u03b8\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1 (Greek)\n|\"sudden rash\"\n|-\n|Hungary\n|H\u00e1romnapos l\u00e1z (Hungarian)<br />Hatodik betegs\u00e9g (Hungarian)\n|\"three-day fever\"<br />\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Iceland\n|Mislingabr\u00f3\u00f0ir (Icelandic)\n|\"measles' brother\"\n|-\n|Israel\n|Tifrachat vrooda \u05ea\u05e4\u05e8\u05d7\u05ea \u05d5\u05e8\u05d5\u05d3\u05d4 (Hebrew)\n|\"rose/pink rash\"\n|-\n|Italy\n|Sesta malattia (Italian)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Japan\n|\u7a81\u767a\u6027\u767a\u75b9 (Japanese) toppatsuseihasshin\n|\"fast/sudden rash\"\n|-\n|Korea (South)\n|\ub3cc\ubc1c\uc9c4 (Korean) Dolbaljin\n|\"fast/sudden rash\"\n|-\n|Malaysia\n|Campak halus (Malay)\n|\"small/tiny measles\"\n|-\n|Netherlands\n|Zesde ziekte (Dutch)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Norway\n|Fjerde barnesykdom (Norwegian)<ref>Nylander, Gro (2009) \"Lille venn, hva n\u00e5?\"</ref>\n|\"fourth disease\"\n|-\n|Philippines\n|Tigdas Hangin (Tagalog)\n|\"wind measles\"\n|-\n|Poland\n|Gor\u0105czka trzydniowa (Polish)\n|\"three-day fever\"\n|-\n|Romanian\n|Roseola<br />eruptia subita\n|Roseola\n|-\n|Russia\n|\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0435\u043e\u043b\u0430 (Russian)<br />\u0448\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0430\u044f \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044c (Russian)\n|Roseola<br />\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Singapore\n|Ji\u01ce m\u00e1 \u5047\u9ebb (Chinese)\n|\"false measles\"\n|-\n|Slovakia\n|\u0160iesta (detsk\u00e1) choroba (Slovak)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Slovenia\n|\u0160esta bolezen (Slovenian)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|South Africa\n|Roseola (English)\n|\"Roseola\"\n|-\n|Sweden\n|Tredagarsfeber<br />Sj\u00e4tte sjukan (Swedish)\n|\"three-day fever\"<br />Sixth disease\n|-\n|Taiwan\n| M\u00e9igu\u012b zh\u011bn \u73ab\u7470\u75b9 (Chinese)\n|\"rose rash\"\n|-\n|Turkey\n|Alt\u0131nc\u0131 hastal\u0131k (Turkish)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Vietnam\n|S\u1ed1t ph\u00e1t ban (Vietnamese)\n|\"baby rash\"\n|}\n\n==Research==\nHHV-6 has been tentatively linked with [[neurodegenerative disease]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hogestyn |first1=JM |last2=Mock |first2=DJ |last3=Mayer-Proschel |first3=M |title=Contributions of neurotropic human herpesviruses herpes simplex virus 1 and human herpesvirus 6 to neurodegenerative disease pathology. |journal=Neural Regeneration Research |date=February 2018 |volume=13 |issue=2 |pages=211\u2013221 |doi=10.4103/1673-5374.226380 |pmid=29557362|pmc=5879884 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Fifth disease]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n| DiseasesDB      = 5857\n| ICD10           = {{ICD10|B|08|2|b|00}}\n| ICD9            = {{ICD9|057.8}}\n| ICDO            = \n| OMIM            = \n| MedlinePlus     = 000968\n| eMedicineSubj   = emerg\n| eMedicineTopic  = 400\n| eMedicine_mult  = {{eMedicine2|derm|378}} {{eMedicine2|ped|998}}\n| MeshID          = D005077\n| SNOMED CT       = 240559001\n}}\n* {{DermNet|viral/roseola}}\n{{Viral cutaneous conditions}}\n{{Numbered Diseases of Childhood}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Exanthema Subitum}}\n[[Category:Virus-related cutaneous conditions]]\n[[Category:Pediatrics]]\n[[Category:RTT]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Human disease caused by human herpesviruses}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Roseola\n| synonyms        = Exanthema subitum,<ref name=St2014/> roseola infantum,<ref name=St2014/> sixth disease,<ref name=St2014/> baby measles, rose rash of infants, three-day fever\n| image           = Roseola on a 21-month-old girl.jpg\n| caption         = Roseola on a 21-month-old girl\n| field           = [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|Infectious disease]]\n| symptoms        = Fever followed by rash<ref name=St2014/>\n| complications   = [[Febrile seizures]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| onset           = Before the age of three<ref name=St2014/>\n| duration        = Few days<ref name=CDC2017/>\n| types           = \n| causes          = ''[[Human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) or ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7)<ref name=St2014/>\n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = Typically based on symptoms<ref name=St2014/>\n| differential    = [[Measles]], [[rubella]], [[scarlet fever]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = [[Supportive care]]<ref name=St2014/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = Generally good<ref name=St2014/>\n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Roseola''' is an [[infectious disease]] caused by certain types of [[virus]].<ref name=CDC2017>{{cite journal|last1=Campadelli-Fiume|first1=Gabriella|title=Human Herpesvirus 6: An Emerging Pathogen|journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases|volume=5|issue=3|pages=353\u2013366|language=en-us|doi=10.3201/eid0503.990306|pmid=10341172|pmc=2640789|df=|year=1999}}</ref> Most infections occur before the age of three.<ref name=St2014>{{cite journal|last1=Stone|first1=RC|last2=Micali|first2=GA|last3=Schwartz|first3=RA|title=Roseola infantum and its causal human herpesviruses.|journal=International Journal of Dermatology|date=April 2014|volume=53|issue=4|pages=397\u2013403|doi=10.1111/ijd.12310|pmid=24673253}}</ref> Symptoms vary from absent to the classic presentation of a fever of rapid onset followed by a rash.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/> The fever generally lasts for three to five days.<ref name=St2014/> The rash is generally pink and lasts for less than three days.<ref name=St2014/> Complications may include [[febrile seizures]], with serious complications being rare.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/>\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nIt is caused by either ''[[human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) or ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7).<ref name=St2014/> Spread is usually through the [[saliva]] of those who are otherwise healthy.<ref name=St2014/><ref name=CDC2017/> However, it may also spread from the mother to baby during pregnancy.<ref name=St2014/> Diagnosis is typically based on symptoms but can be confirmed with blood tests.<ref name=St2014/> Low numbers of [[white blood cell]]s may also be present.<ref name=St2014/>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nTreatment includes sufficient fluids and medications to treat the fever.<ref name=St2014/> Nearly all people are infected at some point in time.<ref name=CDC2017/> Males and females are affected equally often.<ref name=St2014/> The disease was first described in 1910 while the causal virus was determined in 1988.<ref name=St2014/> The disease may reactivate in those with a [[immunocompromised|weakened immune system]] and may result in significant health problems.<ref name=CDC2017/>\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nRoseola typically affects children between six months and two years of age, and begins with a sudden high [[fever]] (39\u201340&nbsp;\u00b0C; 102.2-104&nbsp;\u00b0F). In rare cases, this can cause febrile convulsions (also known as [[febrile seizure]]s or \"fever fits\") due to the sudden rise in body temperature, but in many cases the child appears normal. After a few days the fever subsides, and just as the child appears to be recovering, a red rash appears. This usually begins on the trunk (torso) and then spreads to the arms, legs, and neck. The rash is not itchy and may last 1 to 2 days.<ref>[http://www.webmd.com/skin-problems-and-treatments/tc/roseola-topic-overview ''Roseola \u2013 Topic Overview''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727031317/http://www.webmd.com/skin-problems-and-treatments/tc/roseola-topic-overview |date=2008-07-27 }}, webmd.com</ref> In contrast, a child suffering from [[measles]] would usually appear sicker, with symptoms of [[conjunctivitis]], [[coryza|cold-like symptoms]], and a cough, and their rash would affect the face and last for several days. Liver dysfunction can occur in rare cases.\n\nA small percentage of children acquire HHV-6 with few signs or symptoms of the disease. Exanthema subitum occurs in approximately 30% of children during primary HHV-6 infection.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Zerr | first1 = D. M. | last2 = Meier | first2 = A. S. | last3 = Selke | first3 = S. S. | last4 = Frenkel | first4 = L. M. | last5 = Huang | first5 = M. L. | last6 = Wald | first6 = A. | last7 = Rhoads | first7 = M. P. | last8 = Nguy | first8 = L. | last9 = Bornemann | first9 = R. | last10 = Morrow | doi = 10.1056/NEJMoa042207 | first10 = R. A. | last11 = Corey | first11 = L. | title = A Population-Based Study of Primary Human Herpesvirus 6 Infection | journal = New England Journal of Medicine | volume = 352 | issue = 8 | pages = 768\u2013776 | year = 2005 | pmid =  15728809| pmc = }}</ref> Others may show symptoms significant enough that other more serious infections, such as [[meningitis]] or measles should be ruled out. In case of febrile seizures, medical advice can be sought for reassurance. \n\nIn rare cases, HHV-6 can become active in an adult previously infected during childhood and can show signs of [[Infectious mononucleosis|mononucleosis]].<ref name=\"pmid10774474\">{{cite journal |author=Stoeckle MY |title=The spectrum of human herpesvirus 6 infection: from roseola infantum to adult disease |journal=Annu. Rev. Med. |volume=51 |issue= |pages=423\u201330 |year=2000 |pmid=10774474 |doi=10.1146/annurev.med.51.1.423 }}</ref>\n\n==Cause==\n[[File:Hhv-6 (1).jpg|thumb|Electron micrograph of HHV-6]]\nRoseola is caused by two human [[herpesvirus]]es, ''[[human herpesvirus 6]]'' (HHV-6) and ''[[human herpesvirus 7]]'' (HHV-7), which are sometimes referred to collectively as [[Roseolovirus]]. There are two variants of HHV-6 (HHV-6a and HHV-6b) and studies in the US, Europe, Dubai and Japan have shown that exanthema subitum is caused by HHV-6b. This form of HHV-6 infects over 90% of infants by age 2.\n\n==Prevention==\nThere is no specific [[vaccine]] against or treatment for exanthema subitum, and most children with the disease are not seriously ill.\n\n==Treatment==\nMost cases of HHV-6 infection get better on their own.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tesini|first1=BL|last2=Epstein|first2=LG|last3=Caserta|first3=MT|title=Clinical impact of primary infection with roseoloviruses.|journal=Current Opinion in Virology|date=December 2014|volume=9|pages=91\u20136|pmid=25462439|doi=10.1016/j.coviro.2014.09.013|pmc=4267952}}</ref> If [[encephalitis]] occurs [[ganciclovir]] or [[foscarnet]] may be useful.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ongr\u00e1di|first1=J|last2=Ablashi|first2=DV|last3=Yoshikawa|first3=T|last4=Stercz|first4=B|last5=Ogata|first5=M|title=Roseolovirus-associated encephalitis in immunocompetent and immunocompromised individuals.|journal=Journal of NeuroVirology|date=February 2017|volume=23|issue=1|pages=1\u201319|pmid=27538995|doi=10.1007/s13365-016-0473-0|pmc=5329081}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[John Zahorsky]] MD wrote extensively on this disease in the early 20th century, his first formal presentation was to the St Louis Pediatric society in 1909 where he described 15 young children with the illness. In a JAMA article published on Oct 18, 1913 he noted that \"the name 'Roseola infantilis' had an important place in the medical terminology of writers on skin diseases\" but that descriptions of the disease by previous writers tended to confuse it with many other diseases that produce febrile rashes. In this JAMA article Zahorsky reports on 29 more children with Roseola and notes that the only condition that should seriously be considered in the differential diagnosis is German Measles ([[rubella]]) but notes that the fever of rubella only lasts a few hours whereas the prodromal fever of Roseola lasts three to five days and disappears with the formation of a [[morbilliform]] rash.<ref>John Zahorsky. Roseola Infantum. Journal of the American Medical Association. Oct 18, 1913 pages 1446-1450</ref>\n\n==Names==\n{{More citations needed section|date=November 2017}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Country'''\n|'''Local name (language)'''\n|'''Translated name'''\n|-\n|Belgium\n|Driedagenkoorts (Dutch)<br />Zesde ziekte (Dutch)<br />Ros\u00e9ole (French)\n|\"three-day fever\"<br />\"sixth disease\"<br />-\n|-\n|China (PRC)\n|\u6025\u75b9 (Mandarin) j\u00ed zh\u011bn (pinyin)\n|\"fast rash\"\n|-\n|Czech republic\n|\u0160est\u00e1 nemoc (Czech)\n|\"sixth disease\"\n|-\n|Denmark\n|Tredagsfeber (Danish)\n|\"three day fever\"\n|-\n|Estonia\n|Roseool, kolme p\u00e4eva palavik\n|Roseola/three day fever\n|-\n|Finland\n|Vauvarokko (Finnish)\n|\"baby measles\"\n|-\n|France\n|Ros\u00e9ole\n|\"Roseola\"\n|-\n|Germany\n|Drei-Tage-Fieber (German)\n|\"three-day fever\"\n|-\n|Greece\n|\u0391\u03b9\u03c